{"ts":"2026-06-03T22:00:00Z","agent":"orchestrator","action":"hard-rule-add","decision":"Added Hard Rule to CLAUDE.md §Hard-Rules: 'Never ignore a Codex review on a PR'. Every chatgpt-codex-connector inline finding must be (a) fixed via follow-up commit, (b) explicitly rejected with a thread reply, or (c) spun off to a tracked issue — before merge. Triggered by founder noticing Codex's P2 finding on PR #487 (stale ADR-0008→0009 cross-refs) had to be checked manually; that finding had in fact been addressed via commit 76c6657 but the workflow had no codified gate forcing that check.","rationale":"Codex reviews are mechanical, fast, and catch real cross-reference / API-shape drift that human reviewers miss when PRs land at 02:00. Silently admin-merging over findings trains the team to stop reading them — exactly the failure mode the 'Verify rule against MERGED tree' rule was meant to prevent for our own rules. Codifying the gate makes 'check Codex before merge' a non-negotiable step like DCO sign-off.","ref":"CLAUDE.md,PR#487,Codex"}
{"ts":"2026-06-03T22:30:00Z","agent":"founder","action":"rfc-0105-exception-ratify","decision":"Ratified the RFC-0105 EXCEPTION line (Charter §5.13 / RFC-0090 Three-Surface Rule). Watch is the one capability where CLI and MCP are NOT byte-identical tools because their lifecycles genuinely differ — MCP has long-lived start_watch/stop_watch/watch_status; CLI has foreground mycelium watch that exits on Ctrl-C. Both surfaces drive the same mycelium_core::watch::WatchEngine so reactive behavior (debounce/ignore/re-extract/redb persist) is byte-identical by construction. mycelium watch --status will emit the byte-identical watch_status JSON anchor when the CLI follow-up lands. EXCEPTION codified in skills/index-management/SKILL.md frontmatter comment.","rationale":"This was the last open governance item from the v0.1.18 release. The EXCEPTION was always architecturally justified (foreground-vs-server is genuinely surface-shaped, not fakeable parity) and the parity bridge through WatchEngine is verified by the existing tests. Ratifying closes the open ledger item without leaving v0.1.19's first release blocked on a docs gap.","ref":"RFC-0105,Charter§5.13,RFC-0090"}
